.TH _PRINTF 3 "October 2025" "holbertonschool-printf" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion to standard output
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include "main.h"

int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B _printf()
writes output to the standard output stream (stdout) under control of a
format string that specifies how subsequent arguments are converted for
output.

Supported conversion specifiers in this implementation:
.TP
.B %c
Print a single character (argument promoted to
.BR int ).
.TP
.B %s
Print a C string. If the pointer is
.B NULL ,
prints the literal
.BR "(null)" .
.TP
.B %d , %i
Print a signed decimal integer (base 10).
.TP
.B %%
Print a literal percent sign.

If an unknown specifier follows
.B %
(e.g. \fB%!\fR), this implementation prints
.B %
followed by that character (verbatim).

A trailing solitary
.B %
at the end of the format string is considered an error.

This implementation does
.B not
handle flags, field width, precision, length modifiers, or buffered output.
.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, returns the number of characters written (the terminating
null byte is not counted). On error (e.g. \fIformat\fR is \fBNULL\fR, or
the format ends with a lone \fB%\fR),
.B -1
is returned.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
_printf("Hello\\n");                 /* prints: Hello\n */
_printf("Char: %c\\n", 'A');         /* prints: Char: A\n */
_printf("Str: %s\\n", "Hi");         /* prints: Str: Hi\n */
_printf("Num: %d %i\\n", 42, -7);    /* prints: Num: 42 -7\n */
_printf("Percent: %%\\n");           /* prints: Percent: %\n */
_printf("%!\\n");                    /* prints: %!\\n */
.fi
.SH ERRORS
This simplified implementation reports
.B -1
for invalid input as described in
.B RETURN VALUE
. It does not reproduce all error cases of the C library
.BR printf (3) .
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR write (2),
.BR printf (3),
.BR putchar (3),
.BR stdarg (3)
.SH NOTES
Project constraints: no global variables; at most 5 functions per file;
compiled with \-Wall \-Werror \-Wextra \-pedantic \-std=gnu89.
Only the specifiers listed above are supported.
.SH AUTHORS
